The Data

At this link, you will find a dataset containing information about heart disease patients: https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/0vrpdnq5asmeulc4gd50y/ha_1.csv?rlkey=ciisalceotl77ffqhqe3kujzv&dl=1

A description of the original dataset can be found here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/45/heart+disease (However, this dataset has been cleaned and reduced, and the people have been given fictious names.)

1. Logistic Regression

Fit a Logistic Regression using only age and chol (cholesterol) as predictors.

For a 55 year old, how high would their cholesterol need to be for the doctors to predict heart disease is present?

How high for the doctors to estimate a 90% chance that heart disease is present?

Code 
ct = ColumnTransformer(
  [
    ("dummify", 
    OneHotEncoder(sparse_output=False, handle_unknown='ignore', drop='first'),
    make_column_selector(dtype_include=object)),
    ("standardize", 
    StandardScaler(), 
    make_column_selector(dtype_include=np.number))
  ],
  remainder = "passthrough"
).set_output(transform = "pandas")

logreg_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ("preprocessing", ct),
    ("logreg", LogisticRegression())
])

logreg_pipeline.fit(df[["age", "chol"]], df["diagnosis"])

from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_hline, geom_vline, annotate, labs, geom_abline

chol_at_0_5 = chol_df.loc[chol_df['pred_prob'].sub(0.5).abs().idxmin(), 'chol']
chol_at_0_9 = chol_df.loc[chol_df['pred_prob'].sub(0.9).abs().idxmin(), 'chol']


(ggplot(chol_df, aes(x = "chol", y = "pred_prob", color = "pred"))+
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0.9, color = "red", linetype = "dashed")+
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5, color = "orange", linetype = "dashed")+
    geom_vline(xintercept=chol_at_0_5, color="orange", linetype="dashed") +
    geom_vline(xintercept=chol_at_0_9, color="red", linetype="dashed") +

    annotate("text", x = chol_at_0_5 + 420, y = 0.45, label = f"Chol50 = {chol_at_0_5:.1f}", color = "orange")+
    annotate("text", x = chol_at_0_9 + 420, y = 0.85, label=f"Chol90 = {chol_at_0_9:.1f}", color = "red")+

    geom_point()+
    labs(title = "Predicted Probability of Heart Attack Diagnosis vs. Cholesterol (LogReg)",
         x = "Cholesterol Level",
         y = "Predicted Probability of Heart Attack Diagnosis"))

For a 55 year old, a Cholesterol Level greater than 367.3 would result in a heart disease diagnosis. In order for doctors to be 90% certain of a heart disease diagnosis, the 55 year olds cholesterol level would need to exceed 1582.

3. Support Vector Classifier

Fit an SVC model using only age and chol as predictors. Dont forget to tune the regularization parameter.

For a 55 year old, how high would their cholesterol need to be for the doctors to predict heart disease is present?

Code 
from sklearn.svm import SVC

ct = ColumnTransformer(
  [
    ("dummify", 
    OneHotEncoder(sparse_output=False, handle_unknown='ignore', drop='first'),
    make_column_selector(dtype_include=object)),
    ("standardize", 
    StandardScaler(), 
    make_column_selector(dtype_include=np.number))
  ],
  remainder = "passthrough"
).set_output(transform = "pandas")

svc_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ("preprocessing", ct),
    ("svc", SVC(probability=True))
])

param_grid = {"svc__C": [0.1, 1, 10, 100],
              'svc__kernel': ['linear']}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(svc_pipeline, param_grid, cv=5, scoring="accuracy")
grid_search.fit(df[["age", "chol"]], df["diagnosis"])

best_svc = grid_search.best_estimator_
print(f"Best C: {grid_search.best_params_['svc__C']}")
Best C: 10
Best C: 10

4. Comparing Decision Boundaries

Make a scatterplot of age and chol, coloring the points by their true disease outcome. Add a line to the plot representing the linear separator (aka decision boundary) for each of the three models above.

Code 
# Logistic Regression Coefficients (LogReg)

logreg_intercept = logreg_pipeline.named_steps['logreg'].intercept_[0]

Code 
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_abline, labs, scale_x_continuous
import numpy as np

# Logistic Regression Coefficients (LogReg)
logreg_coef = logreg_pipeline.named_steps['logreg'].coef_[0]
logreg_intercept = logreg_pipeline.named_steps['logreg'].intercept_[0]

# LDA Coefficients (LDA)
lda_coef = lda_pipeline.named_steps['lda'].coef_[0]
lda_intercept = lda_pipeline.named_steps['lda'].intercept_[0]

# SVC Coefficients (SVC with linear kernel)
svc_model = best_svc.named_steps['svc']
svc_coef = svc_model.coef_[0]
svc_intercept = svc_model.intercept_[0]

(ggplot(df, aes(x='chol', y='age', color='diagnosis')) +
        geom_point() +
        # Logistic Regression Decision Boundary (Blue)
        geom_abline(slope=-logreg_coef[0]/logreg_coef[1], intercept=-logreg_intercept/logreg_coef[1], color='blue', linetype='solid') +
        # LDA Decision Boundary (Green)
        geom_abline(slope=-lda_coef[0]/lda_coef[1], intercept=-lda_intercept/lda_coef[1], color='green', linetype='solid') +
        # SVC Decision Boundary (Red)
        geom_abline(slope=-svc_coef[0]/svc_coef[1], intercept=-svc_intercept/svc_coef[1], color='red', linetype='solid') +
        labs(title='Age vs Cholesterol with Decision Boundaries',
             subtitle='Logistic Regression (Blue), LDA (Green), SVC (Red)',
             x='Cholesterol Level', y='Age')+
        scale_x_continuous(limits=[0, 500]))
